Rainfall will decline dramatically after Good Friday, so most Kenyans can expect a relatively dry Easter weekend. Head of meteorological services Peter Ambenje says most parts of the country will have some rain but intensity will decline towards the weekend. However, the showers will pick up on Easter Monday, the day many Kenyans are set to travel back from upcountry. The exceptions could be the Lake Victoria Basin and Rift Valley highlands, which will be have relatively heavier rainfall throughout Easter.  This region  comprises all of Nyanza, as well as Trans Nzoia, Baringo, Uasin Gishu, Elgeyo-Marakwet, Nakuru, Narok, and Kajiado counties. The Central Highlands, including Nairobi, Nyeri, Murang’a, Embu and Meru, will experience cloudy early mornings with rains in a few places until tomorrow. “The remaining early mornings are expected to be cloudy, giving way to sunny intervals,” Ambenje said. The Coastal Strip will experience morning showers over several places tomorrow and on Good Friday. However, the rains will diminish significantly Saturday and Sunday. The Met head said Turkana, West Pokot and Samburu counties will have sunny intervals throughout the period with a chance of showers and thunderstorms over few places on Easter Monday afternoon. Northeastern Kenya will experience morning rains over few places Friday and Saturday. “The showers are expected to be heavy on Saturday around Mandera,” he said. The southeastern lowlands comprising Kitui, Makueni, Machakos and Taita Taveta, will remain cloudy in the early morning with evening showers today, tomorrow and on Easter Monday. “Sunny intervals will predominate in the afternoon on the remaining days,” he sa